In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims the week of August 8 to August 14, 2010, as National Health Center Week. The article highlights the important role that community health centers play in providing access to primary and preventive care for underserved communities. It emphasizes that community health centers serve nearly 19 million patients across the country, including those without medical insurance. These centers focus on comprehensive wellness, including diagnosis and treatment of illnesses, preventive care, and outreach and education to meet the unique needs of their local communities. The article also mentions the significant investments made by the Obama Administration in community health centers, including funding from the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act and the Affordable Care Act. These investments aim to expand the capacity of community health centers to serve more patients, regardless of their insurance status or ability to pay, and to stimulate local employment and economic growth. The article concludes by encouraging Americans to celebrate National Health Center Week by visiting their local community health centers and exploring the programs they offer.